# Non-frontier executor fitness tracker (reading-order rule)

[`MANIFESTO.md`](../MANIFESTO.md) §1.2 frames Umbraculum-family projects
as **AI-orchestrated-code projects by design** — frontier models do the
planning and the judgment-dense work; faster/cheaper executors should
be able to mechanically apply the resulting plans. That's the **target**
operating mode. The empirical question — *"how close to that target is
today's executor X on this task family?"* — is answered by a project-owned,
per-run, append-only artifact at
`docs/NON-FRONTIER-EXECUTOR-FITNESS-TRACKER.md`.

This rule is the reading-order discipline that connects plan authors and
executors to that artifact.

## Reading-order rule (hard)

If `docs/NON-FRONTIER-EXECUTOR-FITNESS-TRACKER.md` exists at the active
repo's docs root, you MUST consult it in the following situations:

1. **Before drafting a plan** that will be handed (in whole or in part)
   to a non-frontier AI executor:
   - Read **§10 — What this means for plan authors**. It enumerates the
     load-bearing extra-specifications (enumerate gate skills by name,
     enumerate per-file artifacts not by pattern, pre-author README
     boilerplate, specify `tsc --noEmit` not just `vitest`, document
     cross-agent staging boundaries, escalate choice-points via
     `AskQuestion`, require decision rationale in build-log, document
     per-phase commit policy) that prior runs have shown non-frontier
     executors need to land plans correctly on the first pass.
   - Read **§7 — Conventions compliance matrix** and **§8 — Verdict
     snapshot** to see which conventions the target executor model
     family has historically struggled with. Promote those into
     extra-specific plan instructions.

2. **Before executing a plan** as a non-frontier executor (or before
   simulating one for testing purposes):
   - Read **§6.x — Per-run assessments** entries for your model family,
     particularly the *WRONG-table rows*. Those are the known FAIL
     patterns the model exhibited on the last assessed run; treat them
     as traps to actively avoid, not as *"this won't happen to me."*

3. **After finishing a non-frontier-executor-driven plan** (whether you
   were the executor or the verifier):
   - Append a new run row to §5 (Run index), a new per-run section under
     §6, and new columns to the §7 + §8 matrices. Do NOT edit prior run
     sections — each per-run snapshot is the as-of-that-date record.

## On-demand bootstrap when the tracker is absent

If `docs/NON-FRONTIER-EXECUTOR-FITNESS-TRACKER.md` is absent in the
active repo, this rule is informational only — it does not block. The
tracker is a project-owned artifact whose presence indicates the
project explicitly tracks non-frontier executor performance. Absence is
also a signal — the project either hasn't started tracking yet (early
phase), doesn't yet use non-frontier executors on plan-driven work, or
has decided the tracker discipline isn't worth the per-run overhead.

If the user explicitly asks to set up the tracker (e.g. *"bootstrap our
non-frontier executor fitness tracker"*, *"start tracking Composer
runs"*), do so by:

1. Creating `docs/NON-FRONTIER-EXECUTOR-FITNESS-TRACKER.md` with the
   §1-§4 framing, an empty §5 Run index, placeholder §6/§7/§8 tables,
   and an empty §9 Trend notes section.
2. (Optional but recommended) appending the first run as the worked
   example.

Do NOT auto-create the tracker unprompted. Do NOT overwrite an existing
tracker without explicit user confirmation.

## File ownership (for reference)

- `docs/NON-FRONTIER-EXECUTOR-FITNESS-TRACKER.md` — project-owned,
  versioned in the project's main repo. Append-only per run.
- This rule (`43-non-frontier-executor-fitness-tracker.mdc`) — toolset-
  owned, applies repo-agnostically; carries the reading-order
  discipline.
- The repo-root [`AGENTS.md`](../AGENTS.md) interceptor (if present) may
  also carry a project-local pointer to the tracker — that's the
  belt-and-suspenders pattern for in-repo agents that may or may not
  have this plugin loaded.

## Companion skill (future)

A future companion skill (`append-fitness-tracker-run` or similar) MAY
land under `skills/` to mechanize the §5/§6/§7/§8 column-addition
workflow at the end of a run. Until that skill exists, append run
sections by hand following the structure already in §4 (*How to use
this document*) of the tracker itself.

## Why this is a toolset-common rule, not domain-specific

Non-frontier executor fitness is **language- and stack-agnostic**. The
WRONG-patterns observed on a TypeScript/Node project (gate-skill
skipping, partial coverage on multi-file plan lines, README structural
FAILs, cross-agent commit contamination) are the same WRONG-patterns
that will surface on a Python/PLC project or a PHP/Magento project,
because they're properties of the *executor* — not the codebase. This
rule therefore lives in `umbraculum-toolset-common` alongside the other
language-agnostic discipline rules (DCO sign-off gate, commit-message
ticket prefix, public-endpoint verification).
